rguments, then DuplicateProcessCheckHandler sets the exit code when stopping, and GlobalErrorHandler outputs the failure log. This matches what's documented.\n\nFor the normal execution flow, I'm tracing the callbacks to BatchAction - MultiThreadExecutionHandler triggers callbacks before processing starts and when creating the data reader.  LoopHandler commits and loops until the result set is empty, also calling back to BatchAction. MultiThreadExecutionHandler then calls back after normal completion. The callbacks happen at four key points: before processing starts, when the data reader is created, after business commit, and after all records finish.\n\nWhen there's no data to process in the request management table, LoopHandler returns DataReader.NoMoreRecord without proceeding further.\n\nFor the service closure scenario, ServiceAvailabilityCheckHandler throws a service closure exception, and ProcessResidentHandler catches it, logs an INFO message, and continues the loop back to the beginning.\n\nFor abnormal termination, BatchAction sends a runtime exception when the business process needs to end with an error.  This triggers a transaction rollback and outputs failure logs. LoopHandler handles multiple-commit scenarios by rolling back any uncommitted processing and invoking a callback to the business action. MultiThreadExecutionHandler also performs a callback to the business action after the abnormal termination.\n\nFor graceful process shutdown, the request ID is determined from the batch startup argument '-requestPath', and ProcessResidentHandler detects the process stop request to initiate shutdown.\n\nNow looking at the forced termination flow—when BatchAction throws a ProcessAbnormalEnd exception, it terminates not just the current processing but the entire resident process. LoopHandler rolls back any uncommitted transactions in multi-commit scenarios and triggers the business action callback. ProcessResidentHandler re-throws the ProcessAbnormalEnd exception to halt the loop, and GlobalErrorHandler catches it to output failure logs and return the exception as a result object.\n\nChecking the document structure against the knowledge file—the source has 2 main sections plus an introduction, but the knowledge file shows 4 sections with one appearing to have minimal content related to message-only resident batch processing. I'm seeing that s3 contains just \"なし\" (nothing), which is only 2 characters—this is clearly a placeholder section with no actual content backing it up. The source document only has 2 h2 headings, but the knowledge file has 4 sections total, making s3 an extra section that shouldn't exist. Now I'm checking the hints for s4 to see if they're complete—I can see ProcessResidentHandler, MultiThreadExecutionHandler, DuplicateProcessCheckHandler, and ProcessStopHandler are all there, but the list appears to be cut off at \"Service\". I'm noticing some discrepancies in the knowledge file structure - there's an s3 section marked as \"なし\" (nothing) that doesn't correspond to anything in the source material, which suggests a potential fabrication issue. The more pressing concern is whether certain handlers like StatusCodeConvertHandler and GlobalErrorHandler should be included in the hints since they appear in the actual processing flows, though this feels like a minor gap compared to the structural problems I'm uncovering. Looking at the source structure more carefully, I see the intro paragraph followed by a horizontal rule, then two h2 sections. The knowledge file has four sections where s3 contains only \"なし\" with no corresponding source content—this is the core structural mismatch. The s3 section appears to be a placeholder or transition that doesn't map to anything in the original document, making it an orphaned section that needs to be addressed. Looking at the cross-references more carefully, the source documentation includes several links to related sections that are properly preserved in the knowledge file. I'm verifying that the architectural pattern references and handler documentation links are all accounted for and haven't been omitted or altered in translation.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":19013,"cache_read_input_tokens":18561,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":19013,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5e73f1f0-b647-40f1-a220-c1c03ce99698","uuid":"71898bf4-ddf6-4d14-953d-69f01ce400fa"}
